    description = 'A comprehensive theological treatise by Sheikh Ahmad al-Ahsai (d. 1826), founder of the Shaykhi school of Twelver Shia Islam, examining the fundamental doctrine of divine infallibility (''isma) as it applies to both prophets and the Twelve Imams. This sophisticated work employs Quranic exegesis, hadith analysis, and rational argumentation to establish the theological necessity of infallible religious leadership, addressing the scope, nature, and practical implications of divine protection from error and sin. The treatise systematically defends the Shia position that infallibility extends beyond prophets to include the Imams as divinely appointed guides, while responding to Sunni objections and exploring the mystical dimensions of perfect spiritual authority. As part of the influential Jawami'' al-Kalim collection, this work represents a pivotal contribution to Islamic theological discourse on religious authority, demonstrating the sophisticated rational theology that characterized the Shaykhi school''s approach to traditional Shia doctrine during the late Ottoman period.',
